ions of security to policy experts, Russ Castronovo turns to literature, philosophy, and political theory to show how security provides an organizing principle for collective life in ways that both enhance freedom and limit it. His incisive critique ranges from frontier violence and white racial anxiety to insurgent Black print culture and other forms of early American terror, uncovering the hidden logic of insecurity that structures modern approaches to national defense, counterterrorism, cybersecurity, surveillance, and privacy. Drawing on examples from fiction, journalism, tracts, and pamphlets, Castronovo uncovers the deep affective attachments that Americans have held since the founding to the sources of fear and insecurity that make them feel unsafe.Timely and urgent, American Insecurity and the Origins of Vulnerability sheds critical light on how and why the fundamental political desire for security promotes unease alongside assurance and fixates on risk and danger while clamoring for safety.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aAmerican literaturey18th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aAmerican literaturey19th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aFear of crimezUnited StatesxHistory. 0aPublic safetyzUnited StatesxHistory. 0aRacismzUnited StatesxHistory. 0aSecurity (Psychology) in literature. 0aSecurity (Psychology)zUnited StatesxHistory. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Subjects & Themes / Politics .2bisacsh  aAmerican literature.  aCharles Brockden Brown.  aDavid Walker.  aLiberia.  aThomas Jefferson.  aaesthetics.  abiopolitics.  acolonization.  aeighteenth Century.  agothic.  ainformation.  ainsecurity.  aliberalism.  anineteenth century.  apopulation.  aprint culture.  asecurity.  asettler colonialism.  ashaped contemporary ideas.  astate of emergency.  asublim